liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's been a dramatic day with under siege Qantas boss Alan Joyce stepping down two months earlier than planned amid various controversies. The airline faces allegations it sold tickets to cancelled flights, and has yet to refund around $570 million in flight credits. Chief financial officer Vanessa Hudson will take the reins tomorrow and she has told Qantas staff that the airline will be focused on winning back the trust of its customers. "We've overcome many challenges in the process and right now it feels like we're facing another challenging time." "We know that post-COVID we haven't always delivered to what our customers expect." Ms Hudson says the airline is listening to customers and has heard their frustration. "As a company, our job is to get the balance right between looking after customers, you our people and the business itself." "Right now achieving this balance must first start with our customers." " And that's what we will be focused on with our new management team." Here's the reaction from federal transport minister Catherine King to Mr Joyce's retirement. "The decision by Alan Joyce to stand down as chief executive officer of Qantas marks the end of one era and the start of a new one with both major Australian airlines led by women. His decision to bring forward his retirement from Qantas provides an opportunity for new leadership. I wish Vanessa Hudson every success in her new role."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: New Qantas chief executive speaks

children.content: It's been a dramatic day with under siege Qantas boss Alan Joyce stepping down two months earlier than planned amid various controversies.
The airline faces allegations it sold tickets to cancelled flights, and has yet to refund around $570 million in flight credits.
Chief financial officer Vanessa Hudson will take the reins tomorrow and she has told Qantas staff that the airline will be focused
on winning back the trust of its customers.
"We've overcome many challenges in the process and right now it feels like we're facing another challenging time."
"We know that post-COVID we haven't always delivered to what our customers expect."
Ms Hudson says the airline is listening to customers and has heard their frustration.
"As a company, our job is to get the balance right between looking after customers, you our people and the business itself."
"Right now achieving this balance must first start with our customers."
" And that's what we will be focused on with our new management team."
Here's the reaction from federal transport minister Catherine King to Mr Joyce's retirement.
"The decision by Alan Joyce to stand down as chief executive officer of Qantas marks the end of one era and the start of a new one with both major Australian airlines led by women.
His decision to bring forward his retirement from Qantas provides an opportunity for new leadership.
I wish Vanessa Hudson every success in her new role."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian dollar has tumbled on bets the Reserve Bank may be down with its interest rate rises. The RBA kept official interest rates on hold today at 4.1 per cent as expected. The local currency was little changed when the decision came out this afternoon, but in late afternoon trade it has lost nearly one per cent of its value to 63.99 US cents. The Australian share market has ended off its lows with the ASX 200 down 0.06 per cent to 7,314. Most sectors ended in the red with utilities, energy, real estate firms, miners and banks among the losers. Healthcare stocks led the gains. Qantas lost its gains and fell 0.2 per cent after the news that chief executive Alan Joyce would step down early. And mineral explorer Chalice Mining (-13.4 per cent) was the biggest loser on the ASX 200 after stockbroker Jefferies cut its rating.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australia dollar falls below 64 US cents
